          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Which countries are felons banned from entering?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-dec-19-3.jpg" alt="Which countries are felons banned from entering?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"> One under-discussed aspect of being a felon is that it can restrict one‚Äôs international movement. This has been discussed more in the case of President-elect Donald Trump. He is the first felon to be president, and many are curious how this could affect his ability to travel for his job. While it is likely that he will get some of it waived and he might be given a diplomatic pass, he could still be denied entry into certain countries.</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Around <a href="https://www.thrillist.com/news/nation/countries-that-dont-allow-felony-convictions-travelers" target="_blank">37 countries</a> besides the United States refuse to let felons enter. Different situations exist, and not every country has a blanket rule. Some, like Japan, will allow felons who have served under a year in jail to enter. Some, like <a href="https://carlsonmeissner.com/blog/what-countries-do-not-allow-entry-if-you-are-a-convicted-felon/" target="_blank">Canada</a>, usually will allow felons after 5 years since their conviction. Some countries seek full disclosure of all criminal records, while others follow the honor system.‚Äã</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Another thing to note is that while some countries allow felons to enter, they might have difficulty getting a residence permit or visa with a felony or even a misdemeanor. Many residency applications ask for a criminal record from a person‚Äôs home country. This has been a problem for some Russian <a href="https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2024/06/14/for-anti-war-russians-abroad-like-me-nowhere-feels-safe-a85404" target="_blank">activists</a> who immigrated abroad with previous convictions.‚Äã</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
